<PB REF="1" MS="y">
<P>THE HISTORY OF THE TURKS.</P>
<P>BEGINNING With the Year 1679.</P>
<P>Being a full Relation Of the La&s;t Troubles in <HI>Hungary,</HI> with the Sieges of <HI>Vienna,</HI> and <HI>Buda,</HI> and all the &s;everal Battles both by SEA and LAND, between the <HI>CHRISTIANS,</HI> and the <HI>T&V;RKS,</HI> until the End of the Year 1698, and 1699.</P>
<P>IN WHICH <HI>The Peace between the Turks.</HI></P>
<P>AND THE Confederate <HI>Chri&s;tian Princes</HI> and <HI>States,</HI> was happily Concluded at <HI>Carlowitz</HI> in <HI>Hungary,</HI> By the Mediation of His Maje&s;ty of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> and the States General of the <HI>&V;nited Provinces.</HI></P>
<P>With the Effigies of the Emperors and others of Note, Engraven at Large upon Copper, which Compleats the Sixth and La&s;t Edition of the Hi&s;tory of the Turks. <HI>In Two Vol. in Folio.</HI></P>
<P>By Sir <HI>PA&V;L RYCA&V;T,</HI> Kt. Eighteen Years Con&s;ul at <HI>Smyrna,</HI> now his Maje&s;ty's Re&s;ident at <HI>Hamburg,</HI> and Fellow of the <HI>Royal Society.</HI></P>
<P><HI>LONDON:</HI> Printed for <HI>Robert Clavell,</HI> in St. <HI>Paul</HI>'s Church-Yard, and <HI>Abel Roper</HI> again&s;t St. <HI>Dun&s;tan</HI>'s Church in <HI>Fleet&s;treet.</HI> MDCC.</P>
